==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*itan-'', from Indo-European ''*h₁ed-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[eta]], Old Saxon [[etan#Old Saxon|etan]] (Dutch [[eten]]), Old High German [[ezzan]] (German [[essen]]), Old Norse [[eta]] (Swedish [[åta]]), Gothic [[𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[ἔδω]], Latin [[edo|edō]], Russian [[ем]], Lithuanian [[esti|ésti]], Old Irish [[ith]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'etan/

===Verb===
'''etan''' 
# to [[eat]]
#:''Ðu scealt greot etan'': you will eat dust.  (Cædmon's ''Metrical Paraphrase'')

